The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Members of the West Bengal Cable TV Operators United Front went on a hunger strike on Wednesday, demanding supply of decoder boxes by Sony. The hunger strike, with two new members joining in every day, will continue till the demand is met, said forum spokesperson Mrinal Chatterjee. The cable operators have been staging demonstrations over the issue for the past 10 days. The members had also demonstrated outside the Sony office on Hazra Road.

 Justice Aniruddha Basu of Calcutta High Court on Wednesday passed an order restraining Rabindra Bharati Society from removing any painting or article by Rabindranath Tagore and other eminent artists from the Jorasanko Thakurbari strong room. The court also asked the society to hand over a photocopy of the register containing the list of paintings and articles kept in the strong room to the authorities of Rabindra Bharati University. The order followed a submission by university lawyer Subrata Mukhopadhaya, who alleged that the society had failed to maintain valuable articles and paintings. 

 Trader Debashish Podder and his father were arrested in Kanchrapara, on the northern fringes of the city, on Wednesday for allegedly murdering Debashishs wife Kakali, 24, and their three-year-old daughter Sana. The two were found hanging from the ceiling of their bedroom at their residence in Badajonpur, Kanchrapara, by local residents earlier in the day, said superintendent of police (North 24-Parganas) Praveen Kumar.

 The Bar association of Calcutta High Court on Wednesday made a representation before the registrar-general of the court seeking steps to bolster security on the premises. In a letter, the association secretary informed the registrar-general that about 5,000 lawyers, 4,000 law clerks, more than 100 court employees and 5,000 litigants regularly visit the court. According to him, entry into the court should be restricted.

 A man around 45 years old was killed after being hit by a vehicle on Rani Rashmoni Avenue on Wednesday morning. He was taken to Medical College and Hospital, where he was pronounced dead. 

 Local residents found a male baby, about a month old, lying abandoned near a temple at Burosibtala, in Naihati, on Wednesday. The crying baby was wrapped in a piece of cloth. Several couples in the area wanted to adopt the child, but police handed it over to the government authorities. 

 Mohammad Anwar, 48, a pavement-dweller, was found lying unconscious near the Calcutta Municipal Corporation office on SN Banerjee Road late on Tuesday. He was taken to NRS Medical College and Hospital, where he was declared dead. Police said Anwar was a resident of Gaya, in Bihar. 

